":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"15844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15844"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.25,0.09,0.33,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8535"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115643"}}}},{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"items","id":"8535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8535"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2024-11-18T23:37:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-24T18:25:25+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2024-11-21T13:31:10+10:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-22 05:19:31"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15844"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"6687"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"13477"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97646"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"3496"},{"type":"tags","id":"5295"},{"type":"tags","id":"8051"},{"type":"tags","id":"9594"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20481"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45231"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97646"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115643"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe question is beyond the expected knowledge of a graduating medical student. \u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic at 32 weeks gestation with a two-week history of an intensely pruritic rash. The rash began on her abdomen around her umbilicus and has spread to involve her trunk and limbs. She is otherwise well with an uncomplicated first pregnancy. She has no significant medical history and takes only prenatal vitamins. She has not started any new creams or other new products, and lives with her husband who does not have any similar rashes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are tense vesicles and bullae on an erythematous base across her abdomen, chest, and arms. The mucous membranes are not involved.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral acyclovir","Oral prednisolone","Topical mupirocin","Topical betamethasone cream","Oral antihistamines alone"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features consistent with pemphigoid gestationis (herpes gestationis), an autoimmune blistering disease of pregnancy and very rarely as a paraneoplastic manifestation. The characteristic presentation includes intensely pruritic vesicles and bullae that typically begin periumbilically and spreads to involve the trunk and limbs. Despite its name, it is not related to herpes virus infection. Indirect immunofluorescence for the autoantibodies and histology help with diagnosis if required though it is often a clinical diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is the treatment of choice for moderate to severe disease which is present in this case. The usual starting dose is 20-40mg daily, which can be adjusted based on clinical response. Systemic corticosteroids are necessary to control the inflammatory process and prevent progression of the disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical betamethasone cream\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be insufficient for treating this condition given its severity and extent. While topical steroids may be used for mild or localised disease, or as an adjunctive therapy, for a case such as this the widespread distribution makes the less appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral acyclovir\u003C/strong\u003E would not be effective as this is not a viral condition. The term \u0027herpes gestationis\u0027 is a historical misnomer and can be misleading; the condition is actually an autoimmune disorder mediated by complement-fixing IgG antibodies against the basement membrane zone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral antihistamines\u003C/strong\u003E may help with symptom control but are not sufficient as primary therapy. While they can help reduce pruritus, they do not address the underlying autoimmune process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical mupirocin\u003C/strong\u003E would only be appropriate if there were evidence of secondary bacterial infection which is not present in this case. It does not address the primary autoimmune process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe condition typically flares near delivery or immediate post-partum period, and may recur in subsequent pregnancies or with oral contraceptive use. There is a risk of premature delivery or small-for-gestational age baby, and the newborn may develop mild, self-limiting blisters due to passive transfer of antibodies for less than one month. Close monitoring during pregnancy and the post-partum period is essential, with adjustment of corticosteroid doses as needed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pemphigoid gestationis is an autoimmune blistering disease of pregnancy requiring prompt treatment with oral corticosteroids.","The condition may affect subsequent pregnancies."],"references":["Pregnancy-specific dermatoses. In: Therapeutic guidelines [online]. 2022 [cited 2025 Aug 12]. Available at: https://www.tg.org.au","Ngan V, Stanway A, Mitchell G.  Pemphigoid gestationis. In: DermNet NZ [online]. 2021.  Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/pemphigoid-gestationis","Parfene CG, Bohiltea RE, Mihai BM, Grigoriu C, Margaritescu I, Chirita AD, Zugravu CA and Pelinescu\u2011Onciul D.  Influence of pemphigoid gestationis on pregnancy outcome: A case report and review of the literature. Experimental and Therapeutic Medicine. 2023.  Available at: https://www.spandidos-publications.com/10.3892/etm.2021.10945"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97646"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15844"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97646"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-24T18:25:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-24T18:25:11+09:30","number":6,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":null,"plagiarismScore":null,"plagiarismReportUrl":null},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8535"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115643"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"6687"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name"